<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-011-271 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 486 020</DOCID><JOURNAL>San Jose Mercury News  Nov 14 1991 p8E(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Bosses, pay structure hinder telecommuting.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Langberg, Mike.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Telecommunicating is a method of working at home recommended bysome interested in environmental protection.andP;  It is mentioned asone of several approaches to reduce traffic; others includedesigning communities so that home and workplace are closetogether and developing more intelligent computerized vehicles.andO;At the California Engineering Foundation's two-day conference,held on Nov 13-14, 1991, The emphasis is on telecommuting at theCalifornia Engineering Foundation's Nov 13-14, 1991 conference.andO;Some experts suggest that as many as 10 percent of the SanFrancisco Bay Area's workers could telecommute immediately.andP;  Thatnumber could rise to one-half if businesses organized their workprocesses to encourage working at home.andP;  The main obstacles seemto be management's reluctance to trust employees and a believethat salaried employees would be unproductive if unsupervised.andO;Changes in compensation and in tax laws are needed, and workersmust be protected from being reclassified as contract or part-timeworkers, thus losing benefits.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TelecommutingEmployee RelationsWork at HomePersonnel ManagementEnvironmental Protection.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>